4\. New Findings from RMC Analysis

These items were discovered during RMC analysis and were not previously
documented in project materials. Several have implications for the POC
build.

4.1 Default Benefit for Married Members Who Fail to Elect

**RMC Section:** §18-410(a)(1)

**Priority:** HIGH --- Affects workspace logic

If a married member and spouse fail to consent to a distribution form,
the default is a 50% Joint and Survivor annuity (actuarial equivalent of
the single life annuity). This is a critical default behavior that the
workspace must enforce: the system cannot allow a married member to
proceed to payment without either a J&S election or a signed spousal
consent form waiving J&S rights.

**Action:** Add default-to-50%-J&S rule in eligibility.yaml. Workspace
must flag married members who have not completed spousal consent.

4.2 Automatic Deferred Member Classification

**RMC Section:** §18-402(10) and §18-408 preamble

**Priority:** HIGH --- Affects process orchestration

The RMC defines a deferred member as one who does not submit the
required retirement application within 30 days of separation. This is
automatic---there is no appeal or extension process in the statute. A
member who misses the 30-day window becomes a deferred member and any
subsequent retirement is a deferred retirement. This answers Q-ELIG-04
from the original questionnaire: there is no appeal process mentioned in
the RMC. The member simply becomes deferred.

**Action:** Process orchestrator must track the 30-day window and alert
CSR staff. After 30 days, member status changes to deferred
automatically.

4.3 Historical Vesting Threshold: 10 Years Pre-1987

**RMC Section:** §18-402(31)

**Priority:** LOW --- Legacy, but affects seed data

Members appointed before January 1, 1987 required 10 years of credited
service to vest (versus 5 years for later members). While no active
member in the current workforce would be affected by this threshold
(they would have vested decades ago), the seed data generator should use
era-appropriate vesting rules for historical member records.

4.4 Rule of 75/85 Must Be Attained While Active

**RMC Section:** §18-402(20)

**Priority:** HIGH --- Affects eligibility engine

The RMC explicitly states that the Rule of 75 (or 85) must be attained
by the member while employed as an active member, prior to termination
of employment. If a member terminates employment after earning the
required service credit but before reaching the minimum age (55/60), the
member may not apply for or receive benefits under the rule until
reaching that minimum age. This clarifies a subtle edge case: the Rule
can be met before minimum age, but benefits cannot start until minimum
age.

**Action:** Eligibility engine must check both the sum threshold AND
minimum age. A deferred member who met the sum while active but hasn\'t
reached minimum age should show as \'Rule met --- benefits available at
age XX.\'

4.5 Death Benefit Schedules Are Age-Specific, Not Formula-Based

**RMC Section:** §18-411(d)(1-2)

**Priority:** MEDIUM --- Confirms calculation approach

The RMC provides explicit dollar-amount schedules for early retirement
death benefits rather than a formula. This means the reduction is by
completed age years, not prorated:

  ----------- ----------------------------- -----------------------------
  **Age**     **Pre-July 2011 (Tiers 1&2)** **On/After July 2011 (Tier
                                            3)**

  65+         \$5,000 (normal)              \$5,000 (normal)

  64          \$4,750                       \$4,500

  63          \$4,500                       \$4,000

  62          \$4,250                       \$3,500

  61          \$4,000                       \$3,000

  60          \$3,750                       \$2,500

  59          \$3,500                       ---

  58          \$3,250                       ---

  57          \$3,000                       ---

  56          \$2,750                       ---

  55          \$2,500                       ---
  ----------- ----------------------------- -----------------------------

This confirms our calculation approach (\$250/year for Tiers 1&2,
\$500/year for Tier 3) and also confirms it is by integer age, not
prorated for months.

4.6 Social Security Make-Up Benefit --- Full Formula Now Available

**RMC Section:** §18-409(i)

**Priority:** OUT OF SCOPE for POC, but documented for future reference

The RMC provides the complete SS Make-Up formula including birth-year
percentage table (0% before 1938, scaling to 15% for 1960+). Applies
only to pre-July 2011 members. Begins at later of retirement or age 62.
Not applicable to disability retirees. Inapplicable to Tier 3 members.
We have the full formula documented for future phases.

4.7 Re-Employment Creates Separate Benefit Calculations (Bridged
Benefit)

**RMC Section:** §18-408(j)(1)

**Priority:** MEDIUM --- Future phase, but affects data model

When a retired member returns to work, benefits are suspended. Upon
subsequent retirement, the member receives a \'bridged benefit\'---two
or more separately calculated retirement benefits combined into one
payment. A re-employed member after July 1, 2011 earns new service under
Tier 3 formula regardless of original tier. The original benefit amount
never changes.

4.8 DRO Alternate Payees Excluded from Health Benefits

**RMC Section:** §18-418(b)(8)

**Priority:** HIGH --- Answers Q-DRO-01

The RMC explicitly states: \'No health benefits available under the plan
shall be paid to, or made available for the use of, the former spouse.\'
This definitively answers Q-DRO-01: the DRO alternate payee is NOT
eligible for IPR or any health benefits from DERP. Case 4 (Robert
Martinez DRO variant) should not include IPR for Patricia.

5\. Updated Questionnaire --- Items for DERP Staff

The following items remain open and require DERP staff input. Items
resolved by RMC analysis have been moved to Sections 2-4. Only items
that cannot be answered from the governing documents remain here.

5.1 Benefit Calculations

**Q-CALC-01 \[HIGH\] \[OPEN\]**

**What actuarial factors does DERP use for Joint & Survivor
reductions?**

**Context:** The RMC (§18-410) states J&S is calculated on an
\'actuarially equivalent basis\' using mortality tables and interest
rates per §18-409(h). The statutory interest rate for actuarial
assumptions is 7.00%. We need the actual J&S factor tables or
methodology to calculate reduced amounts for 100%, 75%, and 50% J&S
options.

**RMC Reference:** §18-409(h)(1-3) and §18-410(a)(1)

> **Resolution:** Continue using illustrative factors per BUILD_HISTORY
> Decision 17. Flag for DERP verification. The statutory 7% rate
> provides a reference point.

**Q-CALC-02 \[MEDIUM\] \[PARTIALLY RESOLVED\]**

**Does DERP apply early retirement reduction by completed years only?**

**Context:** The RMC tables in §18-409(b) list whole-integer ages (55,
56, 57\...) with corresponding percentages. This strongly implies
reduction is by completed years. For example, a member age 55 years 11
months would get the 70% rate (same as age 55 years 0 months). Please
confirm there is no monthly proration.

**RMC Reference:** §18-409(b) --- Tables show integer ages only

> **Resolution:** RMC tables show integer ages only, strongly implying
> completed-years approach. Build with integer-age logic; verify with
> DERP staff.

**Q-CALC-03 \[MEDIUM\] \[OPEN\]**

**How does DERP handle members with less than the full AMS averaging
period?**

**Context:** The RMC states that if a member has fewer than 36 (or 60)
consecutive months, the benefit is averaged over actual consecutive
months. Does DERP encounter this in practice? Are there edge cases with
re-employed members?

**RMC Reference:** §18-409(a)(1-3) --- Each subsection addresses this

5.2 Leave Payout

**Q-LEAVE-01 \[MEDIUM\] \[OPEN\]**

**How does the leave payout appear in payroll data?**

**Context:** The RMC defines the leave payout inclusion/exclusion by
hire date but does not specify how it appears in payroll systems. Is it
added to the final month\'s gross pay, or a separate record? This
affects how the Data Connector retrieves salary data for AMS
calculation.

**RMC Reference:** §18-402(15) --- Gross pay definition

**Q-LEAVE-02 \[MEDIUM\] \[OPEN\]**

**Are there caps on leave payout amounts or anti-spiking provisions?**

**Context:** The RMC does not mention any cap on the leave payout amount
included in gross pay. Does DERP apply any administrative cap, or does
the full accrued leave balance get included? Is there an anti-spiking
provision that limits AMS increases?

**RMC Reference:** §18-402(15) --- No cap language found

5.3 Service Credit

**Q-SVC-01 \[MEDIUM\] \[PARTIALLY RESOLVED\]**

**What are the current purchase-of-service cost factors?**

**Context:** RMC §18-415(c)(2) states cost is \'the actuarial amount
required to provide the credited service based upon the member\'s age
and years of service at the time of election and purchase.\' We have the
Purchase of Service Cost Factor PDFs in our project files. Can DERP
confirm these are current?

**RMC Reference:** §18-415(c)(2)

> **Resolution:** RMC confirms actuarial cost methodology. Cost factor
> PDFs in project files need DERP confirmation of currency.

5.4 Domestic Relations Orders

**Q-DRO-01 \[HIGH\] \[RESOLVED\]**

**Is the DRO alternate payee eligible for IPR at DERP?**

**Context:** Previously open. RMC §18-418(b)(8) explicitly excludes
former spouses from health benefits.

**RMC Reference:** §18-418(b)(8)

> **Resolution:** NO. The RMC states: \'No health benefits available
> under the plan shall be paid to, or made available for the use of, the
> former spouse.\' IPR is a health benefit. Case 4 should not include
> IPR for Patricia.

**Q-DRO-02 \[MEDIUM\] \[PARTIALLY RESOLVED\]**

**Does DERP allow the alternate payee to elect their own payment
option?**

**Context:** RMC §18-418(b)(5)(a) states payments to the former spouse
terminate at their death unless \'the former spouse agrees at the time
of initial payment\...to the option of a continued method of benefit
payment following the member\'s death.\' This implies the former spouse
may have some election options. Can DERP clarify the available options?

**RMC Reference:** §18-418(b)(5)

> **Resolution:** RMC suggests former spouse can agree to continued
> payment after member\'s death. Specific options need DERP
> clarification.

**Q-DRO-03 \[MEDIUM\] \[OPEN\]**

**Does DERP share COLA increases with DRO alternate payees?**

**Context:** RMC §18-414 describes COLA adjustments to \'retired members
and beneficiaries.\' A DRO former spouse is technically not a
beneficiary. Does the COLA apply to the former spouse\'s portion?

**RMC Reference:** §18-414

5.5 Eligibility & Retirement Processing

**Q-ELIG-01 \[HIGH\] \[RESOLVED\]**

**At what age can a deferred-vested member begin collecting?**

**Context:** Previously open.

**RMC Reference:** §18-408(c) and §18-409(e)

> **Resolution:** Pre-July 2011: Age 55 (with Rule of 75 normal or early
> retirement). On/after July 2011: Age 60. Deferred members can elect
> normal (if Rule of 75/85 was met while active) or early retirement
> with reduction.

**Q-ELIG-02 \[CRITICAL\] \[PARTIALLY RESOLVED\]**

**Can DERP confirm the RMC sections cited are current?**

**Context:** We now have the January 2024 edition. The most recent
ordinance cited is Ord. No. 1424-21 (Dec 13, 2021). Have there been any
amendments since January 2024 that affect benefit formulas, eligibility,
or contribution rates?

**RMC Reference:** Full document --- Jan 2024 edition

> **Resolution:** We have the Jan 2024 edition. Need DERP to confirm no
> amendments since then. The contribution rates show \'Effective January
> 1, 2023\' which is the latest rate change.

**Q-ELIG-03 \[HIGH\] \[PARTIALLY RESOLVED\]**

**Does DERP require that the retirement effective date be the first day
of a month?**

**Context:** RMC §18-408(a) says benefits are \'payable on the first
business day of the calendar month following termination.\' §18-408(b)
says \'payable on the first business day of any month following
termination.\' This implies effective date is always the first of a
month following separation. Please confirm.

**RMC Reference:** §18-408(a-b)

> **Resolution:** RMC strongly implies first-of-month-after-separation.
> Build with this assumption; verify with DERP.

**Q-ELIG-04 \[MEDIUM\] \[RESOLVED\]**

**What happens if a member misses the 30-day application deadline?**

**Context:** Previously open.

**RMC Reference:** §18-402(10) and §18-408 preamble

> **Resolution:** The member automatically becomes a \'deferred member\'
> per §18-402(10). Any subsequent retirement is a deferred retirement
> per §18-408(c). No appeal process is mentioned in the RMC. Benefits
> are paid prospectively only.

